node.text:
Legendary Hawaiian surfer and shaper Ben Aipa sadly passed away last January. Yesterday, on what would’ve been Aipa’s 79th birthday, family and friends from all over the world gathered to scatter his ashes at Ala Moana Bowls on Oahu’s South Shore.
🎥: @peterkingphoto

And he did so accordingly on National Tequila Day. | @josecuervotequila

Strapped with his arsenal of legos, a yoga mat tube simulator, and a hearty imagination, Max Montgomery (@tothemax2) depicts what the majority of us have experienced more times than we’d like to admit – a so-so surf session. But aside from his ingenious editing, what stood out most was Max’s passion for, as he said, “Helping those who often don’t get the chance to surf.”
 
Hit the link in bio to view all entries from the Surfline Spirit of Surfing Cuervo Challenge (@josecuervotequila) and vote for your favorite. Note: entry submission deadline ends on 11:59 p.m. PT Sunday, July 25th, so there’s still time to submit your video and secure your chance for a dream session at Surf Ranch with Gerry Lopez.

Two incredibly deep, incredibly long tubes from the Mentawais during the recent run of swell in Indo. First up, Gabriel Pastori (@gabrielpastori); followed by, Icaro Ronchi (@icaroronchi). "Perfect, eight-foot barrels, all day long, with offshore wind on a beautiful, sunny day with no one around," said Gabriel. "It was real, Good-to-Epic conditions!” And there’s more where that came from. Hit the link in bio to see the full #SwellStory.
🎥: @siboncharters

node.title: Biggest Swell of the Season (So Far) Hits Indonesia

“We showed up to Straddie early in the morning with the plan to shoot water first thing,” said Chris Peel. “When we arrived, to our surprise, there was trawler washed up on the shore. I made the call to hold off shooting water till we were sure it wasn’t full of fish or anything that could increase the you-know-what activity. We could tell it was on — a little wobbly and not perfect -- but for sure on. As the sun appeared over the horizon, @tubzxx stood off into this one just in front of the boat. I checked the boat over, it wasn’t full of fish and thankfully not leaking fuel so after a few more sets I swam out to shoot water which ended up being a bust. At the end of the day, we were left with this image which was pretty unique for that area I guess. They ended up pulling the boat off with a tug that night. Word is the vessel got minimal damage and all crew were ok.‘’ 
📷: @chris_peel_photo

Floridian charger @natemcnasty recently spent a chunk of time motoring around the Mentawais with @nicvonrupp, scoring some of the most uncrowded sessions the islands have seen in ages. And it all culminated with a trip to Greenbush, with well-overhead swell cascading over the tricky, razor-sharp lefthand reefbreak. According to Nate: “That wave was actually the first wave ridden that day. I was kinda nervous not knowing how big or makeable it was because no one was out and, since this was my second time surfing there, I didn’t know exactly what to expect. To get a good one off the bat and make it all the way through felt so good.” Hit the link in bio to read more. (And head to the site to see the full edit of the trip.)

🎥: @tanitripod | @10barrelbrewing

Although surfing’s roots go back to the islands of Polynesia, the sport itself was popularized on the shores of Honolulu, and Waikiki is often regarded as the birthplace of modern surfing. Amongst the crowd today is a core group of female longboarders who regularly surf here. Hit the link in bio for a closer look at the women shredders of Oahu’s South Shore.
📷: @tommypierucki

node.text: Last week, a bomb swell detonated on NSW in Australia. But remnants made their way down to the South Coast, too. The one thing missing? The crowds. As photographer @bigzphoto said: “Because of the lockdown, it was only the locals, which was sick. There’s only a few spots around town and it can get pretty packed with crew from Sydney and elsewhere. But not this time.” Hit the link in bio for the full story.
